text: "What if Superman...?"  What?!   BvS takes place less than 2 years after Superman's first appearance. In that movie, we see an older Bruce Wayne who has been retired from being Batman for many years. We see that Robin suit with the Joker reference on it. Meaning he had to be fairly close to Bruce's age. And if Joker did kill Robin, Batman (especially the serial killer from BvS) would not rest until Joker was dealt with. So if this takes place pre-Batman's retirement, how would this guy know about Superman? If it takes place after BvS, how is Joker still a) alive, and b) young?   Once again, DC shows that whoever is running their film franchise (Snyder) is a moron.

text: Always fun to be that reckless dissenting voice in the fray. This looks derivative as hell: ripped off from "The Dirty Dozen," "Guardians of the Galaxy," a couple dozen other ain't-we-cool films; the high-concept wet dream spawned by a mating of Tarantino and CGI. Deafening. Brash. Full of itself. Full not of characters but behaviors and poses. Margot Robbie is fetching but her line delivery is rudimentary, and how often can Will Smith mine this "Fresh Prince" attitude? Slam me, boys and girls, but "Squad" holds little interest for this long-time comic book lover looking for something a little more engaging than a whoopee cushion of a movie. I'll wait for the reviews, but the trailer leaves me exhausted and unimpressed.

The most sexy of them all was the one from Arkham Asylum for sure, no one can deny that. The only other reference I have would be from the comic Injustice where, once again, she had a costume while being hot, not the other way around.   Maybe I'm nitpicking but Harley costume sure bothers the actress. I honestly don't see why they had to go the route of over sexualized girl.
